{"id":"2304.01780","submitter":"Daniel Valero","authors":"Arnau Bay\\'on, Daniel Valero, M\\'ario J. Franca","title":"Urban Flood Drifters (UFDs): identification, classification and\n  characterisation","comments":"This preprint is currently under revision (04/04/2023)","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.flu-dyn","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  Extreme floods threat lives, assets and ecosystems, with largest impacts\noccurring in urbanised areas. However, flood mitigation schemes generally\nneglect the fact that urban floods carry a considerable amount of solid load.\nIn this study, we define Urban Flood Drifters (UFDs) as loose objects present\nin the urban landscape that can become mobile over certain flow conditions,\nthereafter blocking drainage infrastructure and endangering both downstream and\nupstream communities. Based on post-flood photographic records from 63 major\ninundations of the past quarter-century across 46 countries, we provide a\ncomprehensive analysis of UFDs and its flood-hazard implications. We show that\na variety of vehicles, furniture and a heterogeneous mixture of drifters are\npresent in post-flooding scenarios. Plastic, wood drifters and construction\ndebris represent each about 20% of the material transported in urban floods\n(57.8% together), while only 11.2% corresponds to cars, which is practically\nthe only UFD analysed in flood literature. We develop a UFD-stability diagram,\nshowing that caravans, recreational vehicles (RVs) and also furniture such as\ndumpsters or garden sheds, can be more relevant from a flood hazard\nperspective.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 4 Apr 2023 13:13:20 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-04-05"}
{"id":"2304.01781","submitter":"Marek Eli\\'a\\v{s}","authors":"Antonios Antoniadis and Christian Coester and Marek Eli\\'a\\v{s} and\n  Adam Polak and Bertrand Simon","title":"Mixing predictions for online metric algorithms","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.LG cs.DS","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  A major technique in learning-augmented online algorithms is combining\nmultiple algorithms or predictors. Since the performance of each predictor may\nvary over time, it is desirable to use not the single best predictor as a\nbenchmark, but rather a dynamic combination which follows different predictors\nat different times. We design algorithms that combine predictions and are\ncompetitive against such dynamic combinations for a wide class of online\nproblems, namely, metrical task systems. Against the best (in hindsight)\nunconstrained combination of $\\ell$ predictors, we obtain a competitive ratio\nof $O(\\ell^2)$, and show that this is best possible. However, for a benchmark\nwith slightly constrained number of switches between different predictors, we\ncan get a $(1+\\epsilon)$-competitive algorithm. Moreover, our algorithms can be\nadapted to access predictors in a bandit-like fashion, querying only one\npredictor at a time. An unexpected implication of one of our lower bounds is a\nnew structural insight about covering formulations for the $k$-server problem.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 4 Apr 2023 13:18:00 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-04-05"}
